The MIT library was established in 1862 with the aim of supporting the rapidly growing educational and research missions of the Institute. Over the decades, the library system has expanded significantly, both in terms of physical space and the breadth of its collections.

One of the distinguishing features of the MIT Libraries is their commitment to technological innovation and digital accessibility. The Libraries strive to provide seamless access to electronic resources, fostering a learning environment that leverages digital tools for academic research. In addition to traditional physical materials, MIT Libraries have built an extensive digital repository known as DSpace, which serves as an open access platform for scholarly work produced by the MIT community. This initiative reflects MIT’s dedication to promoting knowledge dissemination on a global scale.

The MIT Libraries consist of several branch libraries, each tailored to meet the needs of different academic disciplines. Notable branches include the Barker Engineering Library, which provides resources central to the Institute’s renowned engineering programs; the Hayden Library, offering extensive collections in the humanities, arts, and sciences;

